For the most part he kept aloof from public life and de- voted himself exclusively to his historical work. The story that he was the tutor of Claudius. afterwards emperor, does not rest on very substantial foundations. It is, however, quite possible that it was on his suggestion that the prince turned his attention to historiography. It was after the accession of Tiberius that he retired to Padua, where he died in 17 A. D.

Judged from the point of view of modern historical re- search, Livy’s work is open to criticism on many counts: there is a very limited use of original sources even where original sources were easily accessible3 he shows but a scant knowledge of legal and constitutional history 3 he is not al- ways wise in his choice of authorities3 and very frequently we find a leaning in the direction of the pieturesque aud the dramatic that does not make for accuracy of statement. Yet whatever defects his work may have, its merits far out- weigh them. And most conspicuous of these is his success in makingdhis subssect vital. He has revivified the dry bones of history found' 1n the jejune accounts of the annal- ists.
